{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17479011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17479011"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:18:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:18:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19092"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19092"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.04,0.24,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86138"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11826"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27974"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86138"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with severe respiratory distress. He has a three-day history of worsening cough and wheeze despite increased use of his salbutamol inhaler. He has a history of moderate persistent asthma and takes regular fluticasone inhaler. He takes no other medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with marked work of breathing. His pulse rate is 145/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 45/min, SpO2 89% on 15 L/min oxygen via non-rebreather mask, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has diffuse wheeze with poor air entry bilaterally. He has already received multiple doses of nebulised salbutamol and ipratropium, intravenous hydrocortisone, and intravenous magnesium sulphate with minimal improvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following intravenous medications is usually utilised as last-line in severe asthma exacerbations in children?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methylprednisolone","Hydrocortisone","Dexamethasone","Magnesium sulphate","Aminophylline"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAminophylline\u003C/strong\u003E is considered a last-line intravenous medication for severe asthma that has not responded to other treatments. While it can be effective, it has a narrow therapeutic window and requires careful monitoring due to potential side effects including arrhythmias, seizures, and vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium sulphate\u003C/strong\u003E has already been administered in this case. While it can be effective in severe asthma by causing bronchodilation and reducing inflammation, it is typically used before considering aminophylline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Edexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E are all systemic corticosteroids that are essential in the management of acute severe asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of severe asthma follows a stepwise approach. Initial therapy includes continuous nebulised short-acting beta-agonists, ipratropium bromide, and systemic corticosteroids. If there is inadequate response, magnesium sulphate is typically the next step. Aminophylline is reserved for cases that have not responded to these measures and should only be used in an intensive care setting with appropriate monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravenous aminophylline is a last-line therapy for severe asthma in children who have not responded to other treatments.","Intravenous magnesium sulphate should be considered before aminophylline in severe asthma not responding to initial therapy.","Systemic corticosteroids are essential early in the management of severe asthma attacks in children."],"references":["Acute asthma. In: The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne clinical practice guidelines. 2023; cited 2025 Feb 1. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/asthma_acute/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19092"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-19T14:41:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-19T14:41:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11826"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86138"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda